Creating Our Linear Model¶

Split our data into training and testing sets. This can be done using sklearn's train_test_split(X, y, test_size) function. This function takes in features (X), the target variable (y), and the test_size (around 0.3)

  • Returns a tuple of X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test sets
In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# features
X = housing_data[['Avg. Area Income', 'Avg. Area House Age', 'Avg. Area Number of Rooms', 
                  'Avg. Area Number of Bedrooms', 'Area Population']]
y = housing_data['Price']

# target value
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3)

Import sklearn's LinearRegression model.

  • Train the model using the fit(train_data, train_data_labels) function.
  • Make predictions using the predict(test_data) function.
In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

lm = LinearRegression()
print(lm.fit(X_train,y_train))
print('Make prediction:\n', lm.predict(X_train))

LinearRegression()

Model Evaluation¶

After the training finished, we can make predictions off of the test data and evaluate our model's performance using the corresponding test data labels (y_test).

  • To get a rough idea of how well the model is predicting, we can make a scatterplot with the true test labels (y_test) on the x-axis, and our predictions on the y-axis. Ideally, we'd like a 45 degree line. The straighter the line, the better our predictions are.
In [ ]:
predictions = lm.predict(X_test)
plt.scatter(y_test,predictions)
plt.show()

In regression analysis, we'd like to see the residuals be normally distributed in regression analysis

In [ ]:
residuals = y_test - predictions
# histogram
sns.histplot(residuals)
plt.show()
  • The most common evaluation metrics for regression problems:
  1. Mean Absolute Error (MAE) is the mean of the absolute value of the errors
  2. Mean Squared Error (MSE) is the mean of the squared errors
  3. Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) is the square root of the mean of the squared errors
  • Comparisons:
  1. MAE is the easiest to understand, because it's the average error.
  2. MSE is more popular than MAE, because MSE "punishes" larger errors, which tends to be useful in the real world.
  3. RMSE is even more popular than MSE, because RMSE is interpretable in the "y" units.

sklearn can calculate all of these metrics. Note: Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) is what we'll most commonly use

  • Instruction: Pass the true labels (y_test) and our predictions
In [ ]:
from sklearn import metrics

print('MAE:', metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions))
print('MSE:', metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions))
print('RMSE:', np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)))

MAE: 80310.2562631866
MSE: 10206012525.38491
RMSE: 101024.8114345427

Coefficient of determination (R^2), which is the percentage of variation in y explained by all the x variables

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

r2_score = r2_score(y_test, predictions)
print('R2 Score:', r2_score)
if (r2_score >= 0.70):
    print('Good!')
else:
    print('Bad!')
# print((r2_score >= 0.7) ? 'good' : 'bad')

R2 Score: 0.9182179228493511
Good!

Interpret our model's coefficients by calling coef_ on the linear model.

  • Use the coefficients with pandas DataFrame (visual purposes).
  • Use intercept_ to get the intercept.
In [ ]:
coeff_df = pd.DataFrame(lm.coef_, X.columns, columns=['Coefficient'])

intercept_df = pd.DataFrame(lm.intercept_, X.columns, columns=['Intercept'])

df = pd.DataFrame()

df['Intercept'] = intercept_df
df['Coefficient'] = coeff_df
df
